,"body":"May 2, 1851 — thirteen years to the day after his brother Edmund, born May 2, 1838. The Tyler brothers shared a birthday a generation apart."}],"sources":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[{"type":"family_orbit","related_id":"X03329","display_label":"was the patent-medicine magnate father of his wife Cornelia","link_text":"Dr. Charles Osgood"},{"type":"professional_peer","related_id":"X03325","display_label":"fought at Powder River in March; he rode there in November","link_text":"Capt. Alexander Moore"}],"quotes":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"statues":[],"bio":{"first_name":"Augustus Cleveland","last_name":"Tyler","display_name":"Col. Augustus Cleveland Tyler","gender":"male","photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1781302518/58094586_128347168840_olklue.jpg","bio_blurb":"Cavalry officer turned American tea planter"},"military_service":[{"war":"American Indian Wars","branch":"US Army","rank":"Second Lieutenant","unit":"4th US Cavalry","war_id":"WAR016","notes":"Texas frontier 1873-78; volunteer on Crook’s Powder River Expedition, Nov-Dec 1876; resigned July 1, 1878"},{"war":"Spanish-American War","branch":"US Volunteers","rank":"Colonel","unit":"3rd Connecticut Volunteer Infantry","war_id":"WAR012","notes":"Camps Haven, Meade, and Marion; honorably discharged Jan 31, 1899"}],"career":[{"role":"President","organization":"American Tea Growing Co., Colleton County SC"},{"role":"Director","organization":"Anniston Manufacturing Co."},{"role":"Director","organization":"Union National Bank, New London"}],"birth":{"year":1851,"month":5,"day":2,"city":"Norwich","state":"Connecticut"},"death":{"year":1908,"month":11,"day":27,"city":"New London","state":"Connecticut"},"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM563"},"education":[{"school_name":"Charlier Institute, New York","type":"secondary"},{"school_name":"United States Military Academy","dates":"1873","type":"undergraduate","notes":"Cullum No. 2498"}],"number_of_marriages":1,"slug":"augustus-cleveland-tyler-1851"},"X03328":{"id":"X03328","bio":{"display_name":"Cornelia “Nellie” Osgood Tyler","gender":"female","bio_blurb":"First woman to write Broadway comic opera"},"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"has_descendants_documented":true,"number_of_marriages":1,"tags":[],"sources":[],"birth":{"year":1854,"month":8,"day":31,"city":"Norwich","state":"Connecticut"},"death":{"year":1931,"month":11,"day":7,"city":"New London","state":"Connecticut"},"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"HD6079","date_year":1878,"children_ids":["HD6350","HD6351","HD6352"]}],"parents":{"father_id":"X03329","mother_id":"X03330"},"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM563"},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"arts","header":"The first woman to write Broadway comic opera","body":"Her A Venetian Romance at the Knickerbocker Theater made her the first woman to author a comic opera for a Broadway hearing — though she was “too modest to allow her photographs to be used for the public prints.” Richard Mansfield, a frequent houseguest, pushed the piece to production."},{"number":2,"category":"arts","header":"The dancing-master’s son at her piano","body":"The boy pianist hired for her daughters’ dance party turned out to be the son of the man who had taught her dancing as a girl in Norwich. She installed Frederic Coit Wright as household musician, paid for his training, and wrote the opera with him."},{"number":3,"category":"character","header":"Lady Bountiful of the Pequot colony","body":"Her summer home, The Elm, anchored New London’s aristocratic Pequot colony with the most splendid entertainments; the town called her Lady Bountiful for her charity. Yet she refused to let a single photograph reach the public prints."}],"slug":"cornelia-nellie-osgood-tyler-x03328"}